<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: SEARCH FOR SUCCESSOR TO KORNBLUM BEGINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles County supervisors Tuesday authorized a nationwide search to find a 
successor for beleaguered Chief Medical Examiner-Coroner Ronald N. Kornblum, 
who announced he will step down from the job on July 1. 
</P>
<P>
"That's going to be a real tough one," said Supervisor Kenneth Hahn of the 
recruitment effort. 
</P>
<P>
He noted that the coroner's staff of 15 doctors performed 5,804 autopsies and 
its 160-member staff handled 18,019 investigations last year. 
</P>
<P>
A recent management audit called for 155 changes in the coroner's office after 
finding that staff shortages, coupled with a growing homicide rate, were 
leading to a breakdown in controls and sanitary conditions. 
</P>
<P>
Kornblum, 56, took over the coroner's office in 1982 when Thomas Noguchi, the 
so-called "coroner to the stars," was accused of mismanagement and lost his 
job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
