P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
CAB FIRM LIABLE IN MAN'S DEATH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
RIVERHEAD, N.Y. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A jury has decided that a cab company and driver should pay $1.36 million to 
the family of a man who died after being abandoned in snow five years ago. 
</P>
<P>
The state Supreme Court jury's verdict was returned Tuesday after a two-week 
trial of a wrongful death lawsuit brought by relatives of George Beatty against 
FME Auto Leasing and driver Michael Dsingelis. 
</P>
<P>
Beatty, a 72-year-old retired bank executive, died 150 yards from his 
Huntington house on Feb. 3, 1985. He was being driven home from a saloon but 
was dropped off when the cabbie was unable to find the house, according to the 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
Edward Joachim, lawyer for Beatty's family, said the driver had been directed 
by the company to get rid of the drunken passenger and go to two other calls. 
</P>
<P>
The medical examiner testified that Beatty had downed about 20 drinks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
